  "prompt": "Can I keep savings account if my status changes to NRI? What happens to my PPF and NPS accounts?",
  "response": "Yes, you can keep your savings account when you become an NRI (Non-Resident Indian). However, you'll need to convert it to a Non-Resident Ordinary (NRO) account. Here's a breakdown of what happens to your different accounts when your residential status changes to NRI:\n\n**1. Savings Account:**\n\n*   **Conversion is Mandatory:** You **must** inform your bank about your change in residential status. They will then convert your existing savings account into an NRO account.\n*   **NRO Account:**\n    *   Allows you to manage income earned in India, such as rent, dividends, pension, etc.\n    *   Funds can be freely repatriated (transferred abroad) subject to applicable taxes and regulations. There are often limits on how much can be repatriated per financial year.\n    *   Interest earned on NRO accounts is taxable in India.\n*   **NRE Account (Optional):** You can also open a Non-Resident External (NRE) account. This account is for funds earned outside India that you want to bring into India.  The key advantages of an NRE account are:\n    *   Funds are freely repatriable.\n    *   Interest earned is **tax-free in India**.\n*   **Joint Account:** You can usually hold an NRO account jointly with a resident Indian.\n\n**2. Public Provident Fund (PPF):**\n\n*   **Cannot Extend/Renew:**  Once you become an NRI, you **cannot** extend your PPF account.  You can only maintain the account until its maturity date.\n*   **No New Contributions:** You **cannot** make any further contributions to your PPF account after becoming an NRI.\n*   **Maturity:** Upon maturity, you can close the account and repatriate the funds (principal and interest) subject to applicable Indian laws.  Alternatively, you can choose to keep the account active without any further contributions and earn interest (this is typically only allowed for a specific period).\n*   **Tax Implications:**  The interest earned on PPF is tax-free, even when you are an NRI. The maturity amount is also tax-free.\n\n**3. National Pension System (NPS):**\n\n*   **Account can continue:** You can generally continue to maintain your existing NPS account even after becoming an NRI.\n*   **Contributions:** You can continue to contribute to your NPS account from your NRE/NRO account.\n*   **Taxation:**  The tax implications of NPS for NRIs can be complex and are subject to change.  It's best to consult a tax advisor for the latest regulations.  Generally, contributions made from an NRE account are eligible for deduction under Section 80C (subject to limits).\n*   **Withdrawal:** Rules for withdrawal remain similar, but the tax implications of the withdrawal amount may differ for NRIs compared to resident Indians.\n*   **Nomination:** Ensure you have a valid nomination to your NPS account.\n*   **Know your Scheme:**  Check the specific details of your NPS scheme and contact the Pension Fund Regulatory and Development Authority (PFRDA) or your Point of Presence (POP) for updated regulations for NRIs.\n\n**Key Considerations & Recommendations:**\n\n*   **Inform Your Bank:** This is the most important step.  Failure to notify your bank can lead to penalties and freezing of your accounts.\n*   **Tax Advice:** Consult a qualified tax advisor specializing in NRI taxation. Tax laws are complex and can change frequently.  They can advise you on the most tax-efficient way to manage your Indian investments.\n*   **Repatriation Limits:** Be aware of the limits on how much money you can repatriate from India in a financial year.  These limits can change, so stay updated.\n*   **Documentation:** Keep all necessary documentation related to your accounts, including your NRI status, bank statements, and tax returns.\n*   **FATCA/CRS:** Understand the requirements of the Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FATCA) and the Common Reporting Standard (CRS).  NRIs are required to declare their foreign assets to comply with these regulations.\n\n**In summary:** You can keep your existing accounts, but you need to convert your savings account to an NRO account. You can maintain your PPF until maturity but cannot extend or contribute to it further. You can generally continue with your NPS account, but consult a tax advisor regarding contributions and withdrawals. Always prioritize informing your bank and seeking professional tax advice.\n",
